  "text": "## CRD Validation Schema to OpenAPI V3 Schema Conversion and Publication Chain\n\n### 1. CRD Validation Schema Definition\nCustomResourceDefinitions define their validation schema through the `CustomResourceValidation` type (in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiextensions-apiserver/pkg/apis/apiextensions/types.go:413-417`). The core field is `OpenAPIV3Schema *JSONSchemaProps`, which contains the OpenAPI v3 schema for validating custom resources.\n\n### 2. Structural Schema Extraction\nThe conversion pipeline starts with extracting a structural schema from the OpenAPI JSONSchemaProps:\n\n- **NewStructural()** (`staging/src/k8s.io/apiextensions-apiserver/pkg/apiserver/schema/convert.go:42-99`) converts a CRD's `JSONSchemaProps` (OpenAPI v3 schema) into an internal `Structural` schema representation. This validates that the schema is structurally sound - containing only supported JSON schema constructs while removing forbidden fields like `$ref`, `patternProperties`, etc.\n\n- The **Structural** type (`staging/src/k8s.io/apiextensions-apiserver/pkg/apiserver/schema/structural.go:26-37`) is an internal representation optimized for recursive traversal, containing properties, items, validation rules, and extensions.\n\n### 3. OpenAPI Schema Conversion\nOnce extracted into structural form, the schema is converted back to OpenAPI specification format:\n\n- **ToKubeOpenAPI()** (`staging/src/k8s.io/apiextensions-apiserver/pkg/apiserver/schema/kubeopenapi.go:23-45`) converts the internal Structural schema to go-openapi's `spec.Schema` format. This is a faithful, roundtrippable conversion that preserves all structural schema information.\n\n### 4. OpenAPI Spec Building\nThe CRD controller builds complete OpenAPI v3 specifications:\n\n- **BuildOpenAPIV3()** and **BuildOpenAPIV2()** (`staging/src/k8s.io/apiextensions-apiserver/pkg/controller/openapi/builder/builder.go:198-215`) take a CRD and construct full OpenAPI specifications. The builder:\n  1. Extracts the validation schema for the requested version\n  2. Creates a structural schema via `NewStructural()`\n  3. Builds a go-restful WebService with proper endpoints (GET, LIST, WATCH, CREATE, UPDATE, DELETE, etc.)\n  4. Uses kube-openapi's builder to generate the complete OpenAPI spec with definitions\n\n### 5. Dynamic OpenAPI v3 Publishing Controller\nA controller watches for CRD changes and publishes updated specs:\n\n- **Controller.Run()** (`staging/src/k8s.io/apiextensions-apiserver/pkg/controller/openapiv3/controller.go:85-105`) starts the OpenAPI v3 controller which:\n  1. Watches all CustomResourceDefinition objects via an informer\n  2. Calls **buildV3Spec()** (line 237) for each CRD version to build the OpenAPI v3 spec\n  3. Calls **updateCRDSpec()** (line 212) to store the spec indexed by group/version and CRD name\n  4. Calls **updateGroupVersion()** (line 179) to merge all CRD specs for a group/version and update the service\n\n- The **OpenAPIV3Service** (from vendor/k8s.io/kube-openapi/pkg/handler3/handler.go) is updated via `UpdateGroupVersion()` to serve the merged spec at the `/openapi/v3/apis/{group}/{version}` endpoint.\n\n### 6. API Server Endpoint Registration\nThe API server registers the OpenAPI v3 endpoint during startup:\n\n- **PrepareRun()** (`staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/genericapiserver.go:447-456`) calls `routes.OpenAPI.InstallV3()` to register the handler.\n\n- **InstallV3()** (`staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/routes/openapi.go:52-59`) creates an OpenAPIService and registers it to handle `/openapi/v3` requests, returning discovery documents listing all available group/version specs with their relative URLs and etags for caching.\n\n### 7. HTTP Handler and Endpoint Publishing\nThe kube-openapi handler serves the specs:\n\n- **OpenAPIService** (`vendor/k8s.io/kube-openapi/pkg/handler3/handler.go:49-60`) maintains a registry of OpenAPI v3 specifications indexed by group version.\n\n- **RegisterOpenAPIV3VersionedService()** registers HTTP handlers that:\n  1. Serve the root `/openapi/v3` discovery document listing all group/versions\n  2. Serve `/openapi/v3/apis/{group}/{version}` with the full spec for each group/version\n  3. Include etags for client-side caching of specs\n  4. Support both JSON and Protocol Buffer formats\n\n### Summary of Key Files and Functions\nThe complete chain flows through:\n1. CRD validation spec definition (`CustomResourceValidation`)\n2. Structural schema extraction (`NewStructural()`)\n3. OpenAPI conversion (`ToKubeOpenAPI()`)\n4. Spec building (`BuildOpenAPIV3()`)\n5. Dynamic controller updates (`Controller.buildV3Spec()`, `updateCRDSpec()`)\n6. API server endpoint setup (`PrepareRun()`, `InstallV3()`)\n7. HTTP handler serving (`OpenAPIService`, `RegisterOpenAPIV3VersionedService()`)\n\nThis architecture allows Kubernetes to dynamically publish OpenAPI v3 specifications for custom resources as they are defined via CustomResourceDefinitions, enabling clients to discover and validate custom resource schemas without restarting the API server."
